  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nR_T\n=\n\\lim_{x\\to p}\n\\left(\nR+f(x)\n\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $R$ denote the ordinary Ricci scalar curvature of the manifold.  \nNear the TZP, ordinary curvature may diverge because the metric becomes degenerate.\n\nTo produce a finite Trawinistic curvature quantity, introduce a regulator function $f(x)$ designed to cancel or absorb the divergent contribution near $p$:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nR_{\\mathrm{reg}}(x)=R(x)+f(x).\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe TZP curvature is then defined as the limiting regularized curvature at the zero point:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nR_T\n=\n\\lim_{x\\to p}\n\\left(\nR+f(x)\n\\right).\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\n$R_T$ is the curvature seen through the TZP regulator. It separates uncontrolled singular behavior from a finite Trawinistic curvature condition.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
